# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: core-data
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Cocoa consists of the Foundation Kit, Application Kit, and Core Data frameworks, as included by the `Cocoa.h` header file, and the libraries and frameworks included by those, such as the C standard library and the Objective-C runtime.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Cocoa applications are typically developed using the development tools provided by Apple, specifically Xcode (formerly Project Builder) and Interface Builder (now part of Xcode), using the programming languages Objective-C or Swift.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] However, the Cocoa programming environment can be accessed using other tools.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] It is also possible to write Objective-C Cocoa programs in a simple text editor and build it manually with GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) or Clang from the command line or from a makefile.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] For end users, Cocoa applications are those written using the Cocoa programming environment.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Such applications usually have a familiar look and feel, since the Cocoa programming environment provides a lot of common UI elements (such as buttons, scroll bars, etc.), and automates many aspects of an application to comply with Apple's human interface guidelines.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] For iOS, iPadOS, tvOS, and watchOS, APIs similar to Application Kit, named UIKit and WatchKit, are available; they include gesture recognition, animation, and a different set of graphical control elements that are designed to accommodate the specific platforms they target.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Foundation Kit and Core Data are also available in those operating systems.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] It is used in applications for Apple devices such as the iPhone, the iPod Touch, the iPad, the Apple TV, and the Apple Watch.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Cocoa continues the lineage of several software frameworks (mainly the *App Kit* and *Foundation Kit*) from the NeXTSTEP and OpenStep programming environments developed by NeXT in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Apple acquired NeXT in December 1996, and subsequently went to work on the Rhapsody operating system that was to be the direct successor of OPENSTEP.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] It was to have had an emulation base for classic Mac OS applications, named *Blue Box*.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] The OpenStep base of libraries and binary support was termed *Yellow Box*.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Rhapsody evolved into Mac OS X, and the Yellow Box became Cocoa.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Thus, Cocoa classes begin with the letters *NS*, such as NSString or NSArray.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] These stand for the original proprietary term for the OpenStep framework, NeXTSTEP.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Much of the work that went into developing OpenStep was applied to developing Mac OS X, Cocoa being the most visible part.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] For example, NeXTSTEP and OpenStep used Display PostScript for on-screen display of text and graphics, while Cocoa depends on Apple's Quartz (which uses the Portable Document Format (PDF) imaging model, but not its underlying technology).
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Cocoa also has a level of World Wide Web support, including the NSURL and WebKit HTML classes, and others, while OpenStep had only rudimentary support for managed network connections via NSFileHandle classes and Berkeley sockets.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] The API toolbox was originally called “Yellow Box” and was renamed to Cocoa - a name that had been already trademarked by Apple.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Apple's *Cocoa* trademark had originated as the name of a multimedia project design application for children.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] The name was intended to evoke "Java for kids", as it ran embedded in web pages.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] The original "Cocoa" program was discontinued following the return of Steve Jobs to Apple.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] At the time, Java was a big focus area for the company, so “Cocoa” was used as the new name for “Yellow Box” because, in addition to the native Objective-C usage, it could also be accessed from Java via a bridging layer.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Even though Apple discontinued support for the Cocoa Java bridge, the name continued and was even used for the Cocoa Touch API.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] One feature of the Cocoa environment is its facility for managing dynamically allocated memory.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Foundation Kit's NSObject class, from which most classes, both vendor and user, are derived, implements a reference counting scheme for memory management.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Objects that derive from the NSObject root class respond to a `retain` and a `release` message, and keep a retain count.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] A method titled `retainCount` exists, but contrary to its name, will usually not return the exact retain count of an object.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] It is mainly used for system-level purposes.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Invoking it manually is not recommended by Apple.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] A newly allocated object created with `alloc` or `copy` has a retain count of one.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Sending that object a `retain` message increments the retain count, while sending it a `release` message decrements the retain count.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] When an object's retain count reaches zero, it is deallocated by a procedure similar to a C++ *destructor*.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] `dealloc` is not guaranteed to be invoked.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Starting with Objective-C 2.0, the Objective-C runtime implemented an optional garbage collector, which is now obsolete and deprecated in favor of Automatic Reference Counting (ARC).
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] In this model, the runtime turned Cocoa reference counting operations such as "retain" and "release" into no-ops.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] The garbage collector does not exist on the iOS implementation of Objective-C 2.0.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Garbage collection in Objective-C ran on a low-priority background thread, and can halt on Cocoa's user events, with the intention of keeping the user experience responsive.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] The legacy garbage collector is still available on Mac OS X version 10.13, but no Apple-provided applications use it.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] In 2011, the LLVM compiler introduced Automatic Reference Counting (ARC), which replaces the conventional garbage collector by performing static analysis of Objective-C source code and inserting retain and release messages as necessary.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Cocoa consists of three Objective-C object libraries called *frameworks*.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Frameworks are functionally similar to shared libraries, a compiled object that can be dynamically loaded into a program's address space at runtime, but frameworks add associated resources, header files, and documentation.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] The Cocoa frameworks are implemented as a type of bundle, containing the aforementioned items in standard locations.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] A key part of the Cocoa architecture is its comprehensive views model.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] This is organized along conventional lines for an application framework, but is based on the Portable Document Format (PDF) drawing model provided by Quartz.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] This allows creating custom drawing content using PostScript-like drawing commands, which also allows automatic printer support and so forth.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Since the Cocoa framework manages all the clipping, scrolling, scaling and other chores of drawing graphics, the programmer is freed from implementing basic infrastructure and can concentrate on the unique aspects of an application's content.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] The Smalltalk teams at Xerox PARC eventually settled on a design philosophy that led to easy development and high code reuse.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Cocoa's design is a fairly, but not absolutely strict application of MVC principles.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Under OpenStep, most of the classes provided were either high-level View classes (in AppKit) or one of a number of relatively low-level model classes like NSString.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Compared to similar MVC systems, OpenStep lacked a strong model layer.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] No stock class represented a "document," for instance.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] During the transition to Cocoa, the model layer was expanded greatly, introducing a number of pre-rolled classes to provide functionality common to desktop applications.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] In Mac OS X 10.3, Apple introduced the NSController family of classes, which provide predefined behavior for the controller layer.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] These classes are considered part of the Cocoa Bindings system, which also makes extensive use of protocols such as Key-Value Observing and Key-Value Binding.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] The term 'binding' refers to a relationship between two objects, often between a view and a controller.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Bindings allow the developer to focus more on declarative relationships rather than orchestrating fine-grained behavior.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] With the arrival of Mac OS X 10.4, Apple extended this foundation further by introducing the Core Data framework, which standardizes change tracking and persistence in the model layer.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] In effect, the framework greatly simplifies the process of making changes to application data, undoing changes when necessary, saving data to disk, and reading it back in.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] In providing framework support for all three MVC domains, Apple's goal is to reduce the amount of boilerplate or "glue" code that developers have to write, freeing up resources to spend time on application-specific features.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] In most object-oriented languages, calls to methods are represented physically by a pointer to the code in memory.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] This restricts the design of an application since specific *command handling* classes are needed, usually organized according to the chain-of-responsibility pattern.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] While Cocoa retains this approach for the most part, Objective-C's late binding opens up more flexibility.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Under Objective-C, methods are represented by a *selector*, a string describing the method to call.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] When a message is sent, the selector is sent into the Objective-C runtime, matched against a list of available methods, and the method's *implementation* is called.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Since the selector is text data, this lets it be saved to a file, transmitted over a network or between processes, or manipulated in other ways.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] The implementation of the method is looked up at runtime, not compile time.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] There is a small performance penalty for this, but late binding allows the same selector to reference different implementations.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] By a similar token, Cocoa provides a pervasive data manipulation method called *key-value coding* (KVC).
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] This allows a piece of data or property of an object to be looked up or changed at runtime by name.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] The property name acts as a key to the value.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] In traditional languages, this late binding is impossible.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] An object's type need not be known, yet any property of that object can be discovered using KVC.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Also, by extending this system using something Cocoa terms *key-value observing* (KVO), automatic support for undo-redo is provided.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Late static binding is a variant of binding somewhere between static and dynamic binding.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] The binding of names before the program is run is called static (*early*); bindings performed as the program runs are dynamic (*late* or *virtual*).
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] One of the most useful features of Cocoa is the powerful *base objects* the system supplies.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] As an example, consider the Foundation classes `NSString` and `NSAttributedString`, which provide Unicode strings, and the `NSText` system in AppKit, which allows the programmer to place string objects in the GUI.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] `NSText` and its related classes are used to display and edit strings.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Paragraph layout can be controlled automatically or by the user, using a built-in "ruler" object that can be attached to any text view.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Spell checking is automatic, using a system-wide set of language dictionaries.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Unlimited undo/redo support is built in.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Using only the built-in features, one can write a text editor application in as few as 10 lines of code.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] With new controller objects, this may fall towards zero.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] When extensions are needed, Cocoa's use of Objective-C makes this a straightforward task.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Objective-C includes the concept of "categories," which allows modifying existing class "in-place".
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Functionality can be accomplished in a category without any changes to the original classes in the framework, or even access to its source.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] In other common languages, this same task requires deriving a new subclass supporting the added features, and then replacing all instances of the original class with instances of the new subclass.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] The Cocoa frameworks are written in Objective-C.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Cocoa's need for runtime binding means many of Cocoa's key features are not available with Java.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] In 2005, Apple announced that the Java bridge was to be deprecated, meaning that features added to Cocoa in macOS versions later than 10.4 would not be added to the Cocoa-Java programming interface.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] At Apple Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) 2014, Apple introduced a new programming language named Swift, which is intended to replace Objective-C.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Originally, AppleScript Studio could be used to develop simpler Cocoa applications.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] However, as of Snow Leopard, it has been deprecated.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] It was replaced with AppleScriptObjC, which allows programming in AppleScript, while using Cocoa frameworks.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] The Cocoa programming environment can be accessed using other tools with the aid of bridge mechanisms such as PasCocoa, PyObjC, CamelBones, RubyCocoa, and a D/Objective-C Bridge.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] Third-party bindings available for other languages include AppleScript, Clozure CL, Monobjc and NObjective (C#), Cocoa# (CLI), Cocodao and D/Objective-C Bridge, LispWorks, Object Pascal, CamelBones (Perl), PyObjC (Python), FPC PasCocoa (Lazarus and Free Pascal), RubyCocoa (Ruby).
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] A Ruby language implementation named MacRuby, which removes the need for a bridge mechanism, was formerly developed by Apple, while Nu is a Lisp-like language that uses the Objective-C object model directly, and thus can use the Cocoa frameworks without needing a binding.
[src:core-data/cocoa-api] There are also open source implementations of major parts of the Cocoa framework, such as GNUstep and Cocotron, which allow cross-platform Cocoa application development to target other operating systems, such as Microsoft Windows and Linux.
[src:core-data/core-data] Just as Cocoa Bindings handle many of the duties of the controller in a model–view–controller design, Core Data handles many of the duties of the data model.
[src:core-data/core-data] Among other tasks, it handles change management, serializing to disk, memory footprint minimization and queries against the data.
[src:core-data/core-data] Core Data describes data with a high level data model expressed in terms of entities and their relationships plus fetch requests that retrieve entities meeting specific criteria.
[src:core-data/core-data] Code can retrieve and manipulate this data on a purely object level without having to worry about the details of storage and retrieval.
[src:core-data/core-data] The controller objects available in Interface Builder can retrieve and manipulate these entities directly.
[src:core-data/core-data] When combined with Cocoa bindings the UI can display many components of the data model without needing background code.
[src:core-data/core-data] For example: a developer might be writing a program to handle vCards.
[src:core-data/core-data] In order to manage these, the author intends to read the vCards into objects, and then store them in a single larger XML file.
[src:core-data/core-data] Using Core Data the developer would drag their schema from the data designer in Xcode into an interface builder window to create a GUI for their schema.
[src:core-data/core-data] They could then write standard Objective-C or Swift code to read vCard files and put the data into Core Data managed entities.
[src:core-data/core-data] From that point on the author's code manipulates these Core Data objects, rather than the underlying vCards.
[src:core-data/core-data] Connecting the `Save` menu item to the appropriate method in the controller object will direct the controller to examine the object stack, determine which objects are dirty, and then re-write a Core Data document file with these changes.
[src:core-data/core-data] Core Data is organized into a large hierarchy of classes, though interaction is only prevalent with a small set of them.
[src:core-data/core-data] Core Data can serialize objects into XML, binary, or SQLite for storage.
[src:core-data/core-data] With the release of Mac OS X 10.5 Leopard, developers can also create their own custom atomic store types.
[src:core-data/core-data] Each method carries advantages and disadvantages, such as being human readable (XML) or more memory efficient (SQLite).
[src:core-data/core-data] This portion of Core Data is similar to the original Enterprise Objects Framework (EOF) system, in that one can write fairly sophisticated queries.
[src:core-data/core-data] Unlike EOF, it is not possible to write your own SQL, as the underlying store may not be SQL-based.
[src:core-data/core-data] Recently, Core Data store for ODBC has been made available in ODBC framework.
[src:core-data/core-data] If you have the Xcode Data Model file, you can read and write files in that format freely.
[src:core-data/core-data] Unlike EOF, though, Core Data is not currently designed for multiuser or simultaneous access unless you use ODBC framework.
[src:core-data/core-data] Schema migration is also non-trivial, almost always requiring code.
[src:core-data/core-data] If other developers have access to and depend upon your data model, you may need to provide version translation code in addition to a new data model if your schema changes.
[src:core-data/core-data] Core Data owes much of its design to an earlier NeXT product, Enterprise Objects Framework (EOF).
[src:core-data/core-data] EOF was an object-relational mapping for high-end SQL database engines such as Microsoft SQL Server and Oracle.
[src:core-data/core-data] EOF's purpose was twofold: first, to connect to the database engine and hide the implementation details; second, to read the data out of the relational format and translate that into a set of objects.
[src:core-data/core-data] Developers typically interacted only with the objects, which simplified development of complex programs, at the cost of some setup to map the data to the objects.
[src:core-data/core-data] The EOF object model was deliberately designed to make the resulting programs work in a document-like fashion; the user could edit the data locally in memory, and then write out all changes with a single Save command.
[src:core-data/core-data] Throughout its history, EOF contained a number of bits of useful code that were not otherwise available under NeXTSTEP/OpenStep.
[src:core-data/core-data] For instance, EOF required the ability to track which objects were dirty so the system could later write them out.
[src:core-data/core-data] This was presented to the developer not only as a document-like system, but also in the form of an unlimited Undo command stack, with each command applied to the data represented as an undoable action.
[src:core-data/core-data] Many developers complained that this state management code was far too useful to be isolated in EOF, and it was later moved into the Cocoa API during the transition to Mac OS X.
[src:core-data/core-data] Initially, what was not translated was EOF itself.
[src:core-data/core-data] EOF was used primarily along with another OpenStep-era product, WebObjects, which was an application server originally based on Objective-C.
[src:core-data/core-data] At the time, Apple was in the process of porting WebObjects to the Java programming language, and as part of this conversion, EOF became much more difficult to use from Cocoa.
[src:core-data/core-data] Once again, there was considerable complaining among 3rd party developers.
[src:core-data/core-data] One critical realization is that the object state management system in EOF did not really have anything to do with relational databases.
[src:core-data/core-data] The same code could be, and was, used by developers to manage graphs of other objects as well.
[src:core-data/core-data] In this role, the really useful parts of EOF were those that automatically built the object sets from the raw data, and then tracked them.
[src:core-data/core-data] It is this concept that forms the basis of Core Data.
[src:core-data/object-graph] In computer science, in an object-oriented program, groups of objects form a network through their relationships with each other, either through a direct reference to another object or through a chain of intermediate references.
[src:core-data/object-graph] These groups of objects are referred to as **object graphs**, after the mathematical objects called graphs studied in graph theory.
[src:core-data/object-graph] An object graph is a view of an object system at a particular point in time.
[src:core-data/object-graph] Unlike a normal data model such as a Unified Modeling Language (UML) class diagram, which details the relationships between classes, the object graph relates their instances.
[src:core-data/object-graph] Object diagrams are subsets of the overall object graph.
[src:core-data/object-graph] Object-oriented applications contain complex webs of interrelated objects.
[src:core-data/object-graph] Objects are linked to each other by one object either owning or containing another object or holding a reference to another object.
[src:core-data/object-graph] This web of objects is called an object graph and it is the more abstract structure that can be used in discussing an application's state.
[src:core-data/object-graph] An object graph is a directed graph, which might be cyclic.
[src:core-data/object-graph] When stored in RAM, objects occupy different segments of the memory with their attributes and function table, while relationships are represented by pointers or a different type of global handler in higher-level languages.
[src:core-data/object-graph] For instance, a Car class can compose a Wheel one.
[src:core-data/object-graph] In the object graph a Car instance will have up to four links to its wheels, which can be named frontLeft, frontRight, back Left and back Right.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:core-data/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] In computer science, **persistence** refers to the characteristic of state of a system that outlives (persists for longer than) the process that created it.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] This is achieved in practice by storing the state as data in computer data storage.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] Programs have to transfer data to and from storage devices and have to provide mappings from the native programming-language data structures to the storage device data structures.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] Picture editing programs or word processors, for example, achieve state persistence by saving their documents to files.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] Persistence is said to be "orthogonal" or "transparent" when it is implemented as an intrinsic property of the execution environment of a program.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] An orthogonal persistence environment does not require any specific actions by programs running in it to retrieve or save their state.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] Non-orthogonal persistence requires data to be written and read to and from storage using specific instructions in a program, resulting in the use of *persist* as a transitive verb: *On completion, the program persists the data*.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] The advantage of orthogonal persistence environments is simpler and less error-prone programs.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] The term "persistent" was first introduced by Atkinson and Morrison in the sense of orthogonal persistence: they used an adjective rather than a verb to emphasize persistence as a property of the data, as distinct from an imperative action performed by a program.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] The use of the transitive verb "persist" (describing an action performed by a program) is a back-formation.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] Orthogonal persistence is widely adopted in operating systems for hibernation and in platform virtualization systems such as VMware and VirtualBox for state saving.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] Research prototype languages such as PS-algol, Napier88, Fibonacci and pJama, successfully demonstrated the concepts along with the advantages to programmers.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] Using system images is the simplest persistence strategy.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] Notebook hibernation is an example of orthogonal persistence using a system image because it does not require any actions by the programs running on the machine.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] An example of non-orthogonal persistence using a system image is a simple text editing program executing specific instructions to save an entire document to a file.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] Using journals is the second simplest persistence technique.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] Journaling is the process of storing events in a log before each one is applied to a system.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] On startup, the journal is read and each event is reapplied to the system, avoiding data loss in the case of system failure or shutdown.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] The entire "Undo/Redo" history of user commands in a picture editing program, for example, when written to a file, constitutes a journal capable of recovering the state of an edited picture at any point in time.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] Journals are used by journaling file systems, prevalent systems and database management systems where they are also called "transaction logs" or "redo logs".
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] This technique is the writing to storage of only those portions of system state that have been modified (are dirty) since their last write.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] Sophisticated document editing applications, for example, will use dirty writes to save only those portions of a document that were actually changed since the last save.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] Any software layer that makes it easier for a program to persist its state is generically called a persistence layer.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] Most persistence layers will not achieve persistence directly but will use an underlying database management system.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] System prevalence is a technique that combines system images and transaction journals, mentioned above, to overcome their limitations.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] DBMSs use a combination of the dirty writes and transaction journaling techniques mentioned above.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] They provide not only persistence but also other services such as queries, auditing and access control.
[src:core-data/persistence-computer-science] Persistent operating systems are operating systems that remain persistent even after a crash or unexpected shutdown.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Many programming languages have bindings to the SQLite library.
[src:core-data/sqlite] It generally follows PostgreSQL syntax, but does not enforce type checking by default.
[src:core-data/sqlite] This means that one can, for example, insert a string into a column defined as an integer.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Although it is a lightweight embedded database, SQLite implements most of the SQL standard and the relational model, including transactions and ACID guarantees.
[src:core-data/sqlite] However, it omits many features implemented by other databases, such as materialized views and complete support for triggers and ALTER TABLE statements.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Richard Hipp designed SQLite in the spring of 2000 while working for General Dynamics on contract with the United States Navy.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Hipp was designing software used for a damage-control system aboard guided-missile destroyers; the damage-control system originally used HP-UX with an Informix database back-end.
[src:core-data/sqlite] In August 2000, version 1.0 of SQLite was released, with storage based on gdbm (GNU Database Manager).
[src:core-data/sqlite] In September 2001, SQLite 2.0 replaced gdbm with a custom B-tree implementation, adding transaction capability.
[src:core-data/sqlite] In June 2004, SQLite 3.0 added internationalization, manifest typing, and other major improvements, partially funded by America Online.
[src:core-data/sqlite] In 2011, Hipp announced his plans to add a NoSQL interface to SQLite, as well as announcing UnQL, a functional superset of SQL designed for document-oriented databases.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite is one of four formats recommended for long-term storage of datasets approved for use by the Library of Congress.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite was designed to allow the program to be operated without installing a database management system or requiring a database administrator.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Unlike client–server database management systems, the SQLite engine has no standalone processes with which the application program communicates.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Due to the serverless design, SQLite applications require less configuration than client–server databases.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite is called *zero-configuration* because configuration tasks such as service management, startup scripts, and password- or GRANT-based access control are unnecessary.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Access control is handled through the file-system permissions of the database file.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Databases in client–server systems use file-system permissions that give access to the database files only to the daemon process, which handles its locks internally, allowing concurrent writes from several processes.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite stores the entire database, consisting of definitions, tables, indices, and data, as a single cross-platform file, allowing several processes or threads to access the same database concurrently.
[src:core-data/sqlite] It implements this simple design by locking the database file during writing.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Write access may fail with an error code, or it can be retried until a configurable timeout expires.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite read operations can be multitasked, though due to the serverless design, writes can only be performed sequentially.
[src:core-data/sqlite] This concurrent access restriction does not apply to temporary tables, and it is relaxed in version 3.7 as write-ahead logging (WAL) enables concurrent reads and writes.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Since SQLite has to rely on file-system locks, it is not the preferred choice for write-intensive deployments.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite uses PostgreSQL as a reference platform.
[src:core-data/sqlite] "What would PostgreSQL do" is used to make sense of the SQL standard.
[src:core-data/sqlite] One major deviation is that, with the exception of primary keys, SQLite does not enforce type checking; the type of a value is dynamic and not strictly constrained by the schema (although the schema will trigger a conversion when storing, if such a conversion is potentially reversible).
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite implements most of the SQL-92 standard for SQL, but lacks some features.
[src:core-data/sqlite] For example, it only partially provides triggers and cannot write to views (however, it provides INSTEAD OF triggers that provide this functionality).
[src:core-data/sqlite] Its support of ALTER TABLE statements is limited.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite uses an unusual type system for an SQL-compatible DBMS: instead of assigning a type to a column as in most SQL database systems, types are assigned to individual values; in language terms it is *dynamically typed*.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Moreover, it is *weakly typed* in some of the same ways that Perl is: one can insert a string into an integer column (although SQLite will try to convert the string to an integer first, if the column's preferred type is integer).
[src:core-data/sqlite] This adds flexibility to columns, especially when bound to a dynamically typed scripting language.
[src:core-data/sqlite] However, the technique is not portable to other SQL products.
[src:core-data/sqlite] A common criticism is that SQLite's type system lacks the data integrity mechanism provided by statically typed columns, although it can be emulated with constraints like `CHECK(typeof(x)='integer')`.
[src:core-data/sqlite] In 2021, support for static typing was added through STRICT tables, which enforce datatype constraints for columns.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Tables normally include a hidden *rowid* index column, which provides faster access.
[src:core-data/sqlite] If a table includes an INTEGER PRIMARY KEY column, SQLite will typically optimize it by treating it as an alias for the *rowid*, causing the contents to be stored as a strictly typed 64-bit signed integer and changing its behavior to be somewhat like an auto-incrementing column.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite includes an option to create a table without a rowid column, which can save disk space and improve lookup speed.
[src:core-data/sqlite] WITHOUT ROWID tables are required to have a primary key.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite supports foreign key constraints, although they are disabled by default and must be manually enabled with a PRAGMA statement.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Stored procedures are not supported; this is an explicit choice by the developers to favor simplicity, as the typical use case of SQLite is to be embedded inside a host application that can define its own procedures around the database.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite does not have full Unicode support by default for backwards compatibility and due to the size of the Unicode tables, which are larger than the SQLite library.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Full support for Unicode case-conversions can be enabled through an optional extension.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite supports full-text search through its FTS5 loadable extension, which allows users to efficiently search for a keyword in a large number of documents similar to how search engines search webpages.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite includes support for working with JSON through its *json1* extension, which is enabled by default since 2021.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite's JSON functions can handle JSON5 syntax since 2023.
[src:core-data/sqlite] In 2024, SQLite added support for JSONB, a binary serialization of SQLite's internal representation of JSON.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Using JSONB allows applications to avoid having to parse the JSON text each time it is processed and saves a small amount of disk space.
[src:core-data/sqlite] In May 2025, the 25th‑anniversary release SQLite 3.50.0 introduced additional features, including new Unicode functions (`unistr()` and `unistr_quote()`), a new API (`sqlite3_setlk_timeout()`) for setting lock timeouts, improved command‑line tools and rsync utility enhancements, and optimized JSONB.
[src:core-data/sqlite] The maximum supported size for an SQLite database file is 281 terabytes.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite normally stores every table and index in a SQLite database in a single ordinary disk file.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Alternatively, SQLite can be told to keep a SQL database entirely in memory as an in-memory database with the `:memory:` connection string.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite's code is hosted with Fossil, a distributed version control system that uses SQLite as a local cache for its non-relational database format, and SQLite's SQL as an implementation language.
[src:core-data/sqlite] A standalone command-line shell program called *sqlite3* is provided in SQLite's distribution.
[src:core-data/sqlite] It can be used to create a database, define tables, insert and change rows, run queries and manage an SQLite database file.
[src:core-data/sqlite] It also serves as an example for writing applications that use the SQLite library.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite uses automated regression testing prior to each release.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Over 2 million tests are run as part of a release's verification.
[src:core-data/sqlite] The SQLite library has 156,000 lines of source code, while all the test suites combined add up to 92 million lines of test code.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite's tests simulate a number of exceptional scenarios, such as power loss and I/O errors, in addition to testing the library's functionality.
[src:core-data/sqlite] Starting with the August 10, 2009 release of SQLite 3.6.17, SQLite releases have 100% branch test coverage, one of the components of code coverage.
[src:core-data/sqlite] SQLite has four different test harnesses: the original public-domain TCL tests, the proprietary C-language TH3 test suite, the SQL Logic Tests, which check SQLite against other SQL databases, and the dbsqlfuzz proprietary fuzzing engine.
